title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta 92FS Vertec Package
postcontent:
Up for sale is a very rare Beretta 92 Vertec frame 9mm. This is in the Bruniton finish and has been discontinued for a while. The vertec frames give you removable sights, railed M9A1 rail, beveled mag well, and a 1911 grip angle. This pistol is in fantastic working condition. Highly maintained and has a "D" spring installed. This also has the slightly shorter 4.7" match barrel. These Vertecs make the Beretta 92 fit smaller hands and are amazing to hold. I'm the original owner of this particular pistol. Round count is around 800 total. It has some wear on the rail from constant on and off tac light use, and very small holster wear. otherwise it's in great shape! It has 5 mags all factory Beretta. 3 15rd mags and 2 20rd mags. Barrel/bore and chamber are chrome lined, Trigger is very nice and crisp with the D spring installed. :P Will come with extra recoil spring and stock hammer spring. Action is BUTTER SMOOTH!  These are going for around $750 just the pistol on gunbroker, and all of them are the ugly INOX. This is your chance to bag a nice bruniton model!

Selling only because i'm consolidating parts/accessories to glocks.

postcontent:
I have a perfect condition, very very lightly shot, Browning Silver Hunter 20 gauge with 28" barrel. I purchased this shotgun last year and shot it only a handful of times before I received another 20 gauge. I shot about 215 rounds through it, and they were nearly all 3/4 oz. light skeet loads. I patterned it with 5 turkey rounds, 5 goose rounds, and shot 5 goose loads on one early season hunt, so it has barely even been broken in. Because I mostly shoot skeet, I shoot my O/U all the time now, so I am going to let this one leave the gun cabinet. It is a great gun and I honestly hate to lose it, but it literally just sits there and needs someone to shoot it. I bought some aftermarket chokes for hunting as well. It is a great shooter, has never failed to cycle, and is a nice soft shooter and a great upland and waterfowl gun. Perfect for someone carrying it all day, young shooters, or female shooters. I put a 1/16" cheek eez comb pad on the stock to offer a better cheek weld and raise the comb just a bit. It can be easily removed though (I have done this to other firearms and have had no marks or issues with removing it). The firearm comes with factory IC, M, and F Invector Plus chokes, as well as 5 Carlson's extended sporting clays chokes in SKT, IC, LT Mod, M, and IM, and also a Pattern Master short range/decoy choke and a long range choke. I also have an interchangeable HiViz fiber optic front sight on it with optional red, green, or white bead. I have the box and all the papers as well. New, this setup cost me $1384 + tax, I'm asking $1125 O.B.O.  Thanks for looking, and if you have any questions feel free to ask through armslist or call or text: (Six one 6) 55 zero - 37 two zero. I also have more pictures.

And on a side note, if you think a 20 is light for geese, I'm here to tell you it works great. The PatternMaster long range and 1oz. of HEVI-Steel #2 dropped every goose on one shot at 30-35 yards. I do take my 12 most of the time, but I had no better success with my 12 than I did with my 20.

title: For Sale:  LWRC M6A2 (w/ Extras) + Trijicon ACOG
postcontent:
Upgrades:
Magpul CTR stock
Magpul AFG
Troy ambi mag release
Troy ambi bolt release lever
ALG Defense trigger
BCM Gunfighter charging handle
Troy QD sling adapter

LWRC sets the standard for the AR-15, and this example is no exception. It is accurate, reliable, easy to clean – all thanks to the piston system. Shoots like a dream, and with the ALG Defense (sister company of Geiselle) trigger, it feels even better. The fit and finish on an LWRC is second to none - the high standard of quality is apparent throughout this rifle.

I took off the typical SOPMOD stock because that stock amplifies the sound of the buffer/spring in your ear. The Magpul CTR is rock solid with no annoying noises. 

I have added a couple of ambi controls, a QD sling adapter, an AFG, and a BCM charging handle all simply for ergonomic reasons. They all work, and they all work very well.

The Trijicon ACOG (TA31RCO-M4CP, red chevron reticle) is an amazing 4x optic, with clear glass, and fiber-optic illuminated reticle that never needs batteries. It is nearly ideal for this rifle, because the optic was designed around a 14.5in barrel and this rifle has a 14.7in barrel (straight from the factory with a pinned/welded A2 "birdcage" device to comply with the law). The optic is zeroed at 100yds for 55gr ammunition.

This is the pride and joy of my collection, but I am selling it to put the money towards a Rifle Dynamics AK and my own build projects.

BUY IT NOW
The Rock Island Armory 1911 series consists of a product line of single-action recoil operated semi-automatic pistols. They are designed and manufactured by Armscor in Marikina City, Philippines, and distributed in the United States by Armscor USA, located in Pahrump, Nevada.
RIA (Rock Island Armory) 1911s are clones of the US Military G.I. M1911-A1, the standard issue US Service pistol from 1911 to 1985. Most RIA models are targeted for the low-end price point of the 1911 pistol market and are basic entry level MIL-SPEC versions of the 1911, however, the RIA Tactical, Compact, and Match models offer additional semi-custom high end features. The Compact model features a skeletonized hammer and beavertail grip safety while the Tactical model also adds a target-grade hammer and trigger as well as an ambidextrous safety, and enhanced contrast combat sights. Armscor is an ISO 9001 certified-compliant company which manufactures Rock Island pistols using CNC (Computer Numerical Control) equipment. RIA 1911 series pistols are constructed of 4140 chromoly steel with a cast frame, and are available in .45 ACP, .38 Super, 9mm Luger, and .22 TCM chamberings.
The general specifications for Rock Island Armory 1911 pistols are:

title: For Sale:  KelTec PMR ODG
postcontent:
The PMR-30 is a light weight, full size pistol chambered for the flat-shooting .22Magnum cartridge (.22WMR). The PMR-30 operates on a unique hybrid blowback/locked-breech system. This operation system allows for the use of a wide variety of ammunition as it seamlessly adjusts between locked breech and blowback operation, depending on the pressure of the cartridge. It uses a double stack magazine of a new design that holds 30 rounds and fits completely in the grip of the pistol. The trigger is a crisp single action with an over-travel stop. The manual safety is a thumb activated ambidextrous safety lever (up for SAFE, down for FIRE). The slide locks back after the last shot and a manual slide lock lever is also provided. The light, crisp trigger pull and fiber optic sights make the PMR-30 ideal for target shooting and hunting small game.

Slide and barrel are 4140 steel, frame is 7075 aluminum. Grip, slide cover, trigger, mag release, and safety levers are glass reinforced Nylon (Zytel), much like other Kel-Tec Pistols. Magazine is Also Zytel and holds 30 rounds, with round count ports. Other features include: dual opposing extractors for reliability, heel magazine release to aid in magazine retention, dovetailed aluminum front sight, Picatinny accessory rail under the barrel, Urethane recoil buffer, captive coaxial recoil springs. PMR30 disassembles for cleaning by removal of a single pin.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt Army Model 1860 revolver
postcontent:
The Colt Army Model 1860 - It was used as a side arm by Confederate and Union forces in the cavalry, infantry, artillery troops, and navy. This Colt was reputed to be used by the Confederacy and has military proof marks.  The barrel has a period, non-Colt repair, adding to it's Confederate legacy.  The brass was silver plated and the plating is still present, (silver plating is unusual for military firearms), most of the rest of the finish is a grey/black patina.  This Colt is the 4 screw model that was designed for a shoulder stock, though few shoulder stocks were issued.  According to Colt records the serial number (9436) makes it of 1861 manufacture.  It appears to be in good mechanical order but I have not fired it.

title: For Sale/Trade:  WWI French Berthier m16 carbine WITH ammo and clips - now for sale
location: Between Charleston and Goosecreek, Charleston, South Carolina
postcontent:
Can ship upon request. 
Offered here is a French Berthier "Mousqueton de Artillerie Modèle 1892 Modifié 1916". Marked Châtellerault. This rifle is dated 1916 and is marked with the "N" on the receiver. Stock, barrel, and trigger guard match. Lock-up is tight and I have personally fired this weapon at 100 yard range and determined it is just as the little carbine is known to be -- very sturdy and accurate! A real pleasure to shoot. The bore is good and I have found no rust or pitting. Rifling is strong. 

Here is a link to comments on my rifle. One estimate of value was 300 Euros ($315) for the rifle alone.
http://forums.gunboards.com/showthread.php?389846-New-Addition-Berthier-M-16

These guns are not too often found in America. 

Small cut located at bottom of stock is not someone's attempt at making a sporter, but is the site of a French-done wood repair that must have fallen out over the years. This is very common. Also, slot in bottom of stock is not missing sling swivel by accident, but was removed by the French for the Artillery carbine and just never sealed up. Overall, rifle has that nice battle-damaged appearance while still offering a completely strong and serviceable rifle. A piece of history straight from WWI! 

Comes with 4 original 5-shot Mannlicher clips and 48 rounds of black primer (best in my experience) 8mm Lebel ammo. 

Thanks for your time and shoot me an email!

P.S. Ask for more pictures!
